
Git

Git is a Version Control System (VCS).
It is used to track changes in source code and allows multiple developers to work on the same project.

GitHub

GitHub is a remote hosting service for Git repositories.

Git stores code locally, whereas GitHub stores it online.

Git Architecture

Working Directory
(git add)
Staging Area
(git commit)
Local Repository
(git push)
Remote Repository (GitHub)

Working Directory

* Files are created or modified here.
* New files are called Untracked files until they are added.

Staging Area

* Temporary area before committing.
* Files are prepared for the next commit.

Local Repository

* Stores commit history on the local machine.

Remote Repository

* Repository hosted on GitHub/Bitbucket.
* Used for sharing code with others.

Commands

Initialize Git

git init

Initializes the current folder as a Git repository.

Check Status

git status

Displays:

* Untracked files
* Modified files
* Staged files

Add Files

Single file

git add file.txt

All files

git add .

Moves files from Working Directory to Staging Area.

Commit

git commit -m "message"

Moves files from Staging Area to Local Repository.

Connect Local Repository to GitHub

git remote add origin <repository-url>

origin is the default name of the remote repository.

Check Remote

git remote -v

Push

First time

git push -u origin main

or

git push -u origin master

After the first push

git push

Moves commits from Local Repository to Remote Repository.

Pull

git pull

Downloads and merges the latest changes from the remote repository.

Fetch

git fetch

Downloads the latest changes but does not merge them into the current branch.

Clone

git clone <repository-url>

Downloads an existing repository from GitHub to the local machine.

Branch Commands

Check current branch

git branch

Create a new branch

git branch dev1

Create and switch to a new branch

git checkout -b dev1

Switch to an existing branch

git checkout dev1

Merge

git merge dev1

Merges the specified branch into the current branch.

Merge Conflict

Occurs when two branches modify the same line of the same file.

Steps to resolve

1. Edit the conflicted file.
2. Remove the conflict markers.
3. Save the file.
4. Stage the file.
5. Commit the changes.

git add .
git commit -m "Resolved merge conflict"

Restore Commands

Unstage a file

git restore --staged file.txt

Moves a file from Staging Area back to Working Directory.

Discard local changes

git restore file.txt

Restores the file to its last committed version.

Delete Git Repository

rm -rf .git

Removes Git tracking from the project.

Most Frequently Used Commands

git init
git status
git add .
git commit -m "message"
git push
git pull
git fetch
git clone <repository-url>
git branch
git checkout -b branch_name
git checkout branch_name
git merge branch_name
git restore --staged file.txt
git restore file.txt

